WEBVTT

00:00:05.210 --> 00:00:08.390
Now we move from the flight toward the landing.

00:00:09.090 --> 00:00:13.750
For the landing, it's important that we've looked beforehand at what landing pattern we want to fly.

00:00:13.890 --> 00:00:15.810
Is it a right-hand or a left-hand pattern?

00:00:16.270 --> 00:00:21.040
And above all, it's important that we all follow the same rules.

00:00:21.220 --> 00:00:24.500
Because in this phase of the flight we're no longer far from the ground.

00:00:24.800 --> 00:00:27.900
That means we have no more time, or very little time, to react.

00:00:28.500 --> 00:00:33.340
When we have 1000 metres above the ground, if someone doesn't do something the way they should,

00:00:33.340 --> 00:00:36.080
we have relatively long to react and assess the situation.

00:00:36.180 --> 00:00:38.980
When landing, everything happens a bit faster, simply because the ground is close.

00:00:39.380 --> 00:00:43.760
So the principle has to be that we all stick to the landing pattern,

00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:50.490
and so we can guarantee that we see what the other pilot, the one ahead, is doing.

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:55.920
The landing pattern looks like this: we decide on a left-hand or right-hand pattern

00:00:55.920 --> 00:01:01.500
and then we come into the position circles, our altitude-loss circles,

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:04.040
where we bleed off our altitude.

00:01:04.200 --> 00:01:09.480
To start a clean landing pattern, it's important that we circle in the same direction

00:01:09.560 --> 00:01:10.840
in which we're going to do the landing pattern.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:12.860
If we do a right-hand pattern, it's a right-hand circle.

00:01:12.940 --> 00:01:15.080
If we do a left-hand pattern, it's a left-hand circle.

00:01:15.600 --> 00:01:18.860
Then we go to an altitude — the landing pattern — that's healthy.

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:23.420
And that healthy altitude is something you learn to gauge after one, two, three landings.

00:01:23.420 --> 00:01:25.280
I already have it under pretty good control.

00:01:25.700 --> 00:01:29.480
By looking at the visual reference point each time, you notice,

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:31.080
ah, right now I'm still this high.

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:34.180
And as a rule, it's better to come in too high and still land properly

00:01:34.200 --> 00:01:37.400
than too low, because altitude gives you time.

00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:39.340
Low altitude causes stress.

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:45.250
When you fly off from the position circle into the downwind leg,

00:01:46.110 --> 00:01:49.430
don't use visual cues like,

00:01:49.510 --> 00:01:52.850
for example, I'm always at tree height or I'm always at this house-level height

00:01:52.850 --> 00:01:55.010
when I fly the downwind leg.

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:58.130
That can vary, depending on the air mass you're in;

00:01:58.450 --> 00:01:59.750
it doesn't have to be the same at all.

00:01:59.850 --> 00:02:02.170
It also changes completely when there's wind in play.

00:02:02.170 --> 00:02:04.890
That's why it's important to develop a feel here.

00:02:05.350 --> 00:02:08.430
You'll dare to do it; everyone has after two, three, four flights.

00:02:08.510 --> 00:02:09.430
Others need a little more.

00:02:09.850 --> 00:02:13.510
But that's why you're with the instructor on the radio,

00:02:13.570 --> 00:02:15.050
where I can give you nice instructions,

00:02:15.110 --> 00:02:17.150
so that at first you do it a bit remote-controlled

00:02:17.150 --> 00:02:20.110
and after a certain number of flights you can do it on your own.

00:02:21.920 --> 00:02:25.720
Downwind, base, final.

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:30.600
If we notice on the downwind that we're clearly too high,

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:34.010
we can simply turn onto base

00:02:34.010 --> 00:02:36.650
and we can also extend the base leg.

00:02:37.190 --> 00:02:41.690
If we have space, we go far, far forward and make a curve.

00:02:41.690 --> 00:02:44.690
If we're too short, we notice we're not always that much higher.

00:02:44.690 --> 00:02:48.190
Then we can also shorten the whole thing, as shown here.

00:02:48.190 --> 00:02:54.190
Or we can also repeat the base leg with S-turns several times.

00:02:54.190 --> 00:02:57.190
And the S-turns always have to follow proper reference points.

00:02:57.190 --> 00:03:00.690
And the good thing about these S-turns is that at any moment we can

00:03:00.690 --> 00:03:05.690
leave the base leg and turn onto final, if we see it fits.

00:03:05.690 --> 00:03:07.500
Then comes final.

00:03:07.500 --> 00:03:09.500
Final should be straight.

00:03:09.500 --> 00:03:13.000
We can of course make a slight correction

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:14.500
if the wind comes from a bit of an angle.

00:03:14.500 --> 00:03:20.000
But ultimately the important thing is that we fly straight toward the landing point.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:26.810
If we notice we're way too high, there are various options.

00:03:26.810 --> 00:03:29.810
We can, for example, make ourselves big.

00:03:29.810 --> 00:03:34.310
That is, the pilot below the wing creates a lot of drag.

00:03:34.310 --> 00:03:39.520
And whether we sit compactly — then we glide well and have little drag.

00:03:39.520 --> 00:03:41.020
Or we make ourselves big.

00:03:41.020 --> 00:03:43.020
That means we sit up out of the harness,

00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:46.020
make sure that our landing gear, namely the legs, are already ready.

00:03:46.020 --> 00:03:49.020
And then we create a lot of drag and have a poor glide.

00:03:49.020 --> 00:03:52.020
That means we can bleed off altitude efficiently.

00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:55.520
And that's how we approach the landing point.

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:58.520
Another option would be to fly very gentle S-turns.

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:00.020
That's also allowed.

00:04:00.020 --> 00:04:04.520
Or, when we get to it later, to land with little-ears.

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:07.520
We pull the little-ears, the paraglider simply becomes smaller,

00:04:07.520 --> 00:04:08.520
has more sink.

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:11.520
And that way you also have a better chance

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:13.020
of landing on the spot.

00:04:13.020 --> 00:04:16.020
At the briefing, by the way, it's a 30-metre circle

00:04:16.020 --> 00:04:18.520
that you have to hit, inside the circle.

00:04:18.520 --> 00:04:21.520
And then you've passed the landing nicely.

00:04:21.520 --> 00:04:25.980
One more important thing: when you pull the little-ears,

00:04:25.980 --> 00:04:29.090
you have to be aware that your arms are in such a position

00:04:29.090 --> 00:04:31.090
that you can't steer much anymore.

00:04:31.090 --> 00:04:33.090
You can steer with weight shift,

00:04:33.090 --> 00:04:35.090
but your manoeuvrability is limited,

00:04:35.090 --> 00:04:37.090
and you have to keep that in mind.

00:04:37.090 --> 00:04:39.090
So better to land a bit further out

00:04:39.090 --> 00:04:44.090
than do something rashly or under stress.

00:04:44.090 --> 00:04:48.950
That usually doesn't end well.

00:04:48.950 --> 00:04:50.950
Then there are also situations

00:04:50.950 --> 00:04:52.950
where the landing turns out a bit different

00:04:52.950 --> 00:04:54.950
than we'd thought.

00:04:54.950 --> 00:04:57.950
For example, we've flown the landing pattern,

00:04:57.950 --> 00:04:59.950
we looked at the windsock up front,

00:04:59.950 --> 00:05:00.950
and it was always nicely showing

00:05:00.950 --> 00:05:02.950
that we should really land final into the wind,

00:05:02.950 --> 00:05:04.950
as we normally do.

00:05:04.950 --> 00:05:06.950
Now, unfortunately, we suddenly have a tailwind,

00:05:06.950 --> 00:05:08.950
because the wind has simply shifted.

00:05:08.950 --> 00:05:10.950
That's no drama, it's important

00:05:10.950 --> 00:05:12.950
that we follow through with the landing pattern,

00:05:12.950 --> 00:05:14.950
because we decided on this pattern

00:05:14.950 --> 00:05:17.950
and then we just land with a tailwind.

00:05:17.950 --> 00:05:19.950
With a tailwind that means

00:05:19.950 --> 00:05:21.950
we have more speed on final.

00:05:21.950 --> 00:05:25.130
So we have to brake through more quickly,

00:05:25.130 --> 00:05:27.370
more decisively,

00:05:27.370 --> 00:05:29.370
than we're used to on a normal landing.

00:05:29.370 --> 00:05:31.370
On a normal headwind landing

00:05:31.370 --> 00:05:33.370
we can brake through relatively comfortably,

00:05:33.370 --> 00:05:35.370
until below the seat and stay down there,

00:05:35.370 --> 00:05:38.370
but with a tailwind landing we have to be a bit higher

00:05:38.370 --> 00:05:40.380
and really brake down decisively,

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:42.380
so we build a momentum

00:05:42.380 --> 00:05:44.380
in which the wing stands up

00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:46.380
and at exactly that moment we're on the ground.

00:05:46.380 --> 00:05:48.380
Even with a tailwind you can

00:05:48.380 --> 00:05:50.380
make nice landings

00:05:50.380 --> 00:05:53.140
that come down on your feet.

00:05:53.140 --> 00:05:55.140
So a tailwind landing is no drama,

00:05:55.140 --> 00:05:57.140
but rather a point

00:05:57.140 --> 00:05:59.140
you can practice well.

00:05:59.140 --> 00:06:01.140
Of course, we're not talking about 30 km/h tailwind,

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:03.140
but about 5 to 10 km/h of wind

00:06:03.140 --> 00:06:05.140
that you could manage.

00:06:05.140 --> 00:06:07.250
Now it can also happen

00:06:07.250 --> 00:06:09.250
that we have to do a slope landing.

00:06:09.250 --> 00:06:11.250
That can also be the case,

00:06:11.250 --> 00:06:13.250
for example, if a landing site is closed.

00:06:13.250 --> 00:06:15.250
We have no other option.

00:06:15.250 --> 00:06:17.250
The slope landing — it's important

00:06:17.250 --> 00:06:19.250
that we don't, if we have the slope here,

00:06:19.250 --> 00:06:21.250
that we don't simply fly straight into the slope,

00:06:21.250 --> 00:06:23.250
because then the slope's inclination

00:06:23.250 --> 00:06:25.250
really wrecks the calculation

00:06:25.250 --> 00:06:27.250
during the flare,

00:06:27.250 --> 00:06:29.250
but rather we have to land parallel to the slope.

00:06:29.250 --> 00:06:31.250
Then we can make exactly the same landing,

00:06:31.250 --> 00:06:33.250
touch down parallel to the slope,

00:06:33.250 --> 00:06:35.810
then it works just fine.

00:06:35.810 --> 00:06:37.810
Now it can also happen

00:06:37.810 --> 00:06:39.810
that we've missed the landing site

00:06:39.810 --> 00:06:41.810
and might land in a parking lot,

00:06:41.810 --> 00:06:43.810
where cars are standing.

00:06:43.810 --> 00:06:45.810
Or we have a fence in the way

00:06:45.810 --> 00:06:47.810
that we didn't see beforehand.

00:06:47.810 --> 00:06:49.810
On the landing site, the farmer

00:06:49.810 --> 00:06:51.810
put a few cows on the meadow

00:06:51.810 --> 00:06:53.810
and set up a sturdy fence.

00:06:53.810 --> 00:06:55.810
We just didn't see the fence

00:06:55.810 --> 00:06:57.810
and we're flying full-speed at it.

00:06:57.810 --> 00:07:00.460
Now you can say,

00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:02.800
okay, now you can mess up too,

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:04.800
you can't avoid the collision,

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:06.800
but you can at least still bleed off energy.

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:08.800
You can also do that

00:07:08.800 --> 00:07:10.910
simply by

00:07:10.910 --> 00:07:12.990
right over the land

00:07:12.990 --> 00:07:15.070
braking fully through.

00:07:15.070 --> 00:07:17.070
So that the energy is gone,

00:07:17.070 --> 00:07:19.070
because there's a difference

00:07:19.070 --> 00:07:21.070
between flying into a fence at 30 km/h

00:07:21.070 --> 00:07:23.070
or only at 5 km/h, or even 0 km/h.

00:07:23.070 --> 00:07:25.070
Then we can actually land on the fence.

00:07:25.070 --> 00:07:27.070
So during a collision,

00:07:27.070 --> 00:07:29.070
remember to bleed off energy

00:07:29.070 --> 00:07:31.070
and don't just stay up there

00:07:31.070 --> 00:07:33.070
and scream, that doesn't help.

00:07:33.070 --> 00:07:35.380
All that does is get people watching

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:37.380
and you'll have even more spectators

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:39.380
in this embarrassing situation.

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:41.380
Wrong done,

00:07:41.380 --> 00:07:43.380
you can no longer reach the landing site

00:07:43.380 --> 00:07:45.420
and on the way to the landing site

00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:47.420
there are only trees.

00:07:47.420 --> 00:07:49.420
Then a tree landing might be

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:51.420
the worst thing you can do,

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:53.420
before you go somewhere toward a cliff face

00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:55.420
or somewhere even dumber to land.

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:57.420
A tree landing, if you have the option,

00:07:57.420 --> 00:07:59.820
preferably pick the conifer.

00:07:59.820 --> 00:08:01.820
It holds up nicely.

00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:03.820
You can hang on well to the branches,

00:08:03.820 --> 00:08:05.820
as you come down,

00:08:05.820 --> 00:08:07.820
and so, important, fly into it nicely.

00:08:07.820 --> 00:08:09.820
Here, too, bleed off energy

00:08:09.820 --> 00:08:11.820
using the brakes

00:08:11.820 --> 00:08:13.870
and protect your head with your arms

00:08:13.870 --> 00:08:15.870
from those branches.

00:08:15.870 --> 00:08:17.870
Important: there are

00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:19.870
good documentaries on tree rescues.

00:08:19.870 --> 00:08:21.870
The paraglider pilot

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:23.870
who flies into the trees

00:08:23.870 --> 00:08:25.870
is usually quite safe,

00:08:25.870 --> 00:08:27.870
because lots of lines get caught in there.

00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:29.870
That also applies if you had a reserve deployment

00:08:29.870 --> 00:08:31.870
over a forest.

00:08:31.870 --> 00:08:33.870
There's a lot of fabric, lots of lines,

00:08:33.870 --> 00:08:35.870
and they tangle in the branches.

00:08:35.870 --> 00:08:37.870
There are very few cases

00:08:37.870 --> 00:08:39.870
where the pilot has gone through the trees

00:08:39.870 --> 00:08:41.870
all the way to the ground.

00:08:41.870 --> 00:08:43.870
Usually you stay hanging up there,

00:08:43.870 --> 00:08:45.870
and then you're basically safe.

00:08:45.870 --> 00:08:47.870
Most of the accidents that result from that

00:08:47.870 --> 00:08:49.870
happen because people, in the shock —

00:08:49.870 --> 00:08:51.870
and it's clearly a shock most of the time,

00:08:51.870 --> 00:08:53.870
it's an emergency situation —

00:08:53.870 --> 00:08:55.870
want to free themselves

00:08:55.870 --> 00:08:57.870
and then fall.

00:08:57.870 --> 00:08:59.870
Because, for example, in steep terrain

00:08:59.870 --> 00:09:01.870
they're sitting in a tree

00:09:01.870 --> 00:09:03.870
and looking sideways toward the terrain,

00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:05.870
they see it's only 2 metres.

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:07.870
And when you then unbuckle from the harness

00:09:07.870 --> 00:09:09.870
and fall,

00:09:09.870 --> 00:09:11.870
15 metres is absolutely devastating.

00:09:11.870 --> 00:09:13.870
Important, when this happens,

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:15.870
first and foremost, stay calm.

00:09:15.870 --> 00:09:17.870
Calm, calm, calm.

00:09:17.870 --> 00:09:19.870
And then give yourself time

00:09:19.870 --> 00:09:21.870
and say, okay,

00:09:21.870 --> 00:09:23.870
now we have to analyse the situation.

00:09:23.870 --> 00:09:25.870
The smartest thing, if you're

00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:27.870
in a civilised area,

00:09:27.870 --> 00:09:29.870
is to inform mountain rescue anyway,

00:09:29.870 --> 00:09:31.920
to inform the Rega.

00:09:31.920 --> 00:09:33.920
Pretty likely someone has seen

00:09:33.920 --> 00:09:35.920
the crash and maybe even already reported it.

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:37.920
We're glad

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:39.920
that you know where you are,

00:09:39.920 --> 00:09:41.920
whether you're okay,

00:09:41.920 --> 00:09:43.920
and whether you need help.

00:09:43.920 --> 00:09:45.920
And in my view help is needed

00:09:45.920 --> 00:09:47.920
any time you notice

00:09:47.920 --> 00:09:50.060
you're in a tree

00:09:50.060 --> 00:09:52.530
and it's also higher than 1-2 metres.

00:09:52.530 --> 00:09:54.530
Then mountain rescue will come

00:09:54.530 --> 00:09:56.530
and they can help you with that too.

00:09:56.530 --> 00:09:58.900
Even with retrieving the wing it's much easier

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:00.900
than risking a fall,

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:02.900
where, as I said before,

00:10:02.900 --> 00:10:05.070
you can fall from a height.

00:10:05.070 --> 00:10:07.070
So, inform people

00:10:07.070 --> 00:10:09.070
about what's happening and

00:10:09.070 --> 00:10:11.070
wait for help.

00:10:11.070 --> 00:10:13.070
Sometimes patience is needed.

00:10:13.070 --> 00:10:15.070
In our region we have

00:10:15.070 --> 00:10:17.180
a very nice partner

00:10:17.180 --> 00:10:19.180
with the Rega, who are very fast

00:10:19.180 --> 00:10:21.180
and accordingly

00:10:21.180 --> 00:10:23.180
the rescue can be initiated very quickly.

00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:25.180
Another landing situation,

00:10:25.180 --> 00:10:27.180
which hopefully never applies,

00:10:27.180 --> 00:10:29.180
which is why it's marked this way here,

00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:31.180
is the water landing.

00:10:31.180 --> 00:10:33.180
A water landing has to be avoided,

00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:35.180
because a standing body of water

00:10:35.180 --> 00:10:37.180
can get very, very cold in winter

00:10:37.180 --> 00:10:39.180
and you get tangled very quickly

00:10:39.180 --> 00:10:41.180
in lines and so on

00:10:41.180 --> 00:10:43.180
and that can make you incapable

00:10:43.180 --> 00:10:45.180
of swimming.

00:10:45.180 --> 00:10:47.180
It's even worse

00:10:47.180 --> 00:10:49.180
in a river.

00:10:49.180 --> 00:10:51.180
In the river it drifts,

00:10:51.180 --> 00:10:53.180
it's pretty uncontrollable

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:55.180
whether you'll even get out.

00:10:55.180 --> 00:10:57.180
There, if you have the option,

00:10:57.180 --> 00:10:59.180
as early as possible,

00:10:59.180 --> 00:11:01.180
when you see that you'll go into the water,

00:11:01.180 --> 00:11:03.180
open the harness buckles,

00:11:03.180 --> 00:11:05.180
so that you can fly away from the gear immediately.

00:11:05.180 --> 00:11:07.180
But what's important: never jump

00:11:07.180 --> 00:11:09.180
before you hit the water,

00:11:09.180 --> 00:11:11.180
out of the harness.

00:11:11.180 --> 00:11:13.180
Because in the shock moment,

00:11:13.180 --> 00:11:15.180
in the adrenaline you're in,

00:11:15.180 --> 00:11:17.180
you don't have a grip on

00:11:17.180 --> 00:11:19.180
whether you're 5 metres above the water surface

00:11:19.180 --> 00:11:21.180
and jumping or whether you're at 20 metres,

00:11:21.180 --> 00:11:23.180
and that can again have very serious consequences

00:11:23.180 --> 00:11:25.180
if you misjudged it.

00:11:25.180 --> 00:11:27.180
So, a water landing,

00:11:27.180 --> 00:11:29.180
basically avoid it,

00:11:29.180 --> 00:11:31.180
which means, for me,

00:11:31.180 --> 00:11:33.180
I don't go training any manoeuvres

00:11:33.180 --> 00:11:35.180
over water, over a river,

00:11:35.180 --> 00:11:37.180
unless it's in a supervised training,

00:11:37.180 --> 00:11:39.180
such as a SIV course,

00:11:39.180 --> 00:11:41.180
where a boat is always ready out there,

00:11:41.180 --> 00:11:43.180
where you make precise use

00:11:43.180 --> 00:11:45.180
of the water surfaces,

00:11:45.180 --> 00:11:47.180
because the water surfaces are nice,

00:11:47.180 --> 00:11:49.180
we have no obstacles.

00:11:49.180 --> 00:11:51.180
But if I'm just going out for a flight,

00:11:51.180 --> 00:11:55.310
then I avoid water surfaces,

00:11:55.310 --> 00:11:57.310
I avoid rivers and I avoid lakes.

00:11:57.310 --> 00:11:59.310
If the whole landing thing

00:11:59.310 --> 00:12:01.310
didn't work out the way

00:12:01.310 --> 00:12:03.310
you wanted,

00:12:03.310 --> 00:12:05.310
or you see

00:12:05.310 --> 00:12:07.330
that maybe you didn't quite do it

00:12:07.330 --> 00:12:09.330
as nicely as you would have liked

00:12:09.330 --> 00:12:11.330
and you got hurt doing it,

00:12:11.330 --> 00:12:13.540
it's important

00:12:13.540 --> 00:12:15.540
that you know how to take care of an injured person.

00:12:15.540 --> 00:12:17.540
In paragliding we have

00:12:17.540 --> 00:12:19.540
unfortunately a disadvantage,

00:12:19.540 --> 00:12:21.540
that we're in the seated position,

00:12:21.540 --> 00:12:23.540
meaning, when we

00:12:23.540 --> 00:12:25.540
come down from above,

00:12:25.540 --> 00:12:27.540
we're always in the seated position,

00:12:27.540 --> 00:12:29.540
it goes pretty directly onto the spine.

00:12:29.540 --> 00:12:31.540
That's why spinal injuries

00:12:31.540 --> 00:12:33.540
are not uncommon in paragliding

00:12:33.540 --> 00:12:35.540
and when we come up to an injured person,

00:12:35.540 --> 00:12:37.540
it's just as important

00:12:37.540 --> 00:12:39.540
that we know that too.

00:12:39.540 --> 00:12:41.540
That means, basically we have to

00:12:41.540 --> 00:12:43.740
first calm things down and then

00:12:43.740 --> 00:12:45.740
you notice relatively quickly

00:12:45.740 --> 00:12:47.740
how badly or where the pilot is injured.

00:12:47.740 --> 00:12:49.740
Is he really hurt in the back

00:12:49.740 --> 00:12:51.740
and is he breathing,

00:12:51.740 --> 00:12:53.740
is everything still working,

00:12:53.740 --> 00:12:55.740
the best is to leave him lying

00:12:55.740 --> 00:12:57.740
and immediately, right away, inform the Rega,

00:12:57.740 --> 00:12:59.740
so they come with a helicopter

00:12:59.740 --> 00:13:01.860
and can transport him out.

00:13:01.860 --> 00:13:03.860
When the helicopter comes,

00:13:03.860 --> 00:13:05.860
you have to know it generates a lot of wind

00:13:05.860 --> 00:13:07.860
as soon as it lands.

00:13:07.860 --> 00:13:09.860
That means he has to gather the wing,

00:13:09.860 --> 00:13:11.860
maybe with a quick fold,

00:13:11.860 --> 00:13:13.860
pack everything up and weigh it down

00:13:13.860 --> 00:13:15.860
with stones or branches,

00:13:15.860 --> 00:13:17.860
so that nothing can fly away

00:13:17.860 --> 00:13:21.940
and endanger the helicopter.

00:13:21.940 --> 00:13:23.940
Injuries that

00:13:23.940 --> 00:13:26.180
affect the back

00:13:26.180 --> 00:13:28.180
are also important.

00:13:28.180 --> 00:13:30.180
If the pilot wants to sit up

00:13:30.180 --> 00:13:32.180
or wants something to drink,

00:13:32.180 --> 00:13:34.180
it's a normal reaction,

00:13:34.180 --> 00:13:36.180
prevent it.

00:13:36.180 --> 00:13:38.180
He should stay lying,

00:13:38.180 --> 00:13:40.180
don't move, as long as he's responsive,

00:13:40.180 --> 00:13:42.180
and don't give him anything to drink either.

00:13:42.180 --> 00:13:44.180
That's extremely important,

00:13:44.180 --> 00:13:46.180
because we don't know whether he has internal injuries

00:13:46.180 --> 00:13:49.600
or not.

00:13:49.600 --> 00:13:51.600
Now we come to the topic of flying technique.

00:13:51.600 --> 00:13:54.260
It's about

00:13:54.260 --> 00:13:56.260
all of us knowing

00:13:56.260 --> 00:13:58.260
what our wing can actually do,

00:13:58.260 --> 00:14:00.260
or rather, what we can influence,

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:02.260
so that the wing

00:14:02.260 --> 00:14:04.260
glides better

00:14:04.260 --> 00:14:06.260
or sinks less.

00:14:06.260 --> 00:14:08.260
It's quite simply

00:14:08.260 --> 00:14:10.260
visible on this scale,

00:14:10.260 --> 00:14:12.260
that when we say

00:14:12.260 --> 00:14:14.260
we want, with a school wing,

00:14:14.260 --> 00:14:16.260
to get our best glide,

00:14:16.260 --> 00:14:18.260
i.e. we go from point A

00:14:18.260 --> 00:14:20.400
to point B

00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:22.400
as far as possible,

00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:24.400
then our brake

00:14:24.400 --> 00:14:26.400
should be in contact at about 5-15 cm

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:28.400
at the speed

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:30.400
you can read here.

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:32.400
If we want to stay in the air

00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:34.400
as long as possible,

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:36.640
i.e. get the minimum sink,

00:14:36.640 --> 00:14:38.640
and we're not going furthest,

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:40.640
but we're in the air longest in terms of time,

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:42.640
then we have to apply a bit more brake,

00:14:42.640 --> 00:14:44.640
namely already 15-10 km/h,

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:46.640
a bit more than trim speed.

00:14:46.640 --> 00:14:48.640
And if we go minimum speed,

00:14:48.640 --> 00:14:50.640
i.e. what the paraglider

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:52.640
is just barely willing to fly,

00:14:52.640 --> 00:14:54.640
before it heads toward a parachutal stall,

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:56.640
which we'll get to later,

00:14:56.640 --> 00:14:58.640
we're applying quite a lot of brake,

00:14:58.640 --> 00:15:00.640
we're going right down to the hips.

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:02.690
Important: the elbows still face nicely downward.

00:15:02.690 --> 00:15:05.120
And then

00:15:05.120 --> 00:15:07.120
we're at about 40 cm,

00:15:07.120 --> 00:15:09.120
where we're flying in a relatively slow range.

00:15:09.120 --> 00:15:11.120
We can also do the opposite,

00:15:11.120 --> 00:15:13.120
namely accelerate.

00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:15.120
If we accelerate with our foot,

00:15:15.120 --> 00:15:17.260
as is the case for most,

00:15:17.260 --> 00:15:19.260
we can step through,

00:15:19.260 --> 00:15:21.260
then we get a lot of speed back,

00:15:21.260 --> 00:15:23.260
because we're doing nothing else

00:15:23.260 --> 00:15:25.260
than reducing our angle of attack,

00:15:25.260 --> 00:15:27.260
and we get faster.

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:31.420
And so the wing also flies significantly faster.

00:15:31.420 --> 00:15:33.420
Quite simply put, we use the accelerator

00:15:33.420 --> 00:15:35.420
any time

00:15:35.420 --> 00:15:37.500
we have a headwind.

00:15:37.500 --> 00:15:39.500
So in calm air

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:41.500
best glide is naturally best.

00:15:41.500 --> 00:15:43.500
If we have a tailwind,

00:15:43.500 --> 00:15:45.500
a bit more brake is

00:15:45.500 --> 00:15:47.810
best, for minimum sink.

00:15:47.810 --> 00:15:50.880
If we have a headwind,

00:15:50.880 --> 00:15:52.880
then we have to accelerate.

00:15:52.880 --> 00:15:54.880
Quite simply put,

00:15:54.880 --> 00:15:56.880
for understanding,

00:15:56.880 --> 00:15:58.880
we fly 30 km/h,

00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:00.880
we have 30 km/h headwind,

00:16:00.880 --> 00:16:02.880
we'd be standing still.

00:16:02.880 --> 00:16:04.880
Thank god we can accelerate,

00:16:04.880 --> 00:16:06.880
if we can get another 10 km/h or so out of it

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:08.880
and then we do fly 10 km/h forward.

00:16:08.880 --> 00:16:10.880
That would be the advantage,

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:12.880
to still reach the landing site

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:18.460
or wherever we're flying to.

00:16:18.460 --> 00:16:20.740
So there's not only flying

00:16:20.740 --> 00:16:22.740
as such with launch and landing,

00:16:22.740 --> 00:16:24.740
as we've already discussed,

00:16:24.740 --> 00:16:26.740
but it should also be fun.

00:16:26.740 --> 00:16:28.740
There's also so-called soaring.

00:16:28.740 --> 00:16:30.740
When we can use the ridge lift,

00:16:30.740 --> 00:16:33.010
then we're really talking about soaring.

00:16:33.010 --> 00:16:35.010
If it's a regional wind

00:16:35.010 --> 00:16:37.010
blowing up the slope,

00:16:37.010 --> 00:16:39.010
that generates a band of lift,

00:16:39.010 --> 00:16:41.010
and in this band of lift

00:16:41.010 --> 00:16:43.010
we can climb out high above the ridge,

00:16:43.010 --> 00:16:45.010
and that's called soaring.

00:16:45.010 --> 00:16:47.010
It's usually purely wind-driven.

00:16:47.010 --> 00:16:49.010
There's also thermo-dynamic soaring,

00:16:49.010 --> 00:16:51.010
which is somewhat mixed with thermals.

00:16:51.010 --> 00:16:53.010
Here we're talking about soaring.

00:16:53.010 --> 00:16:55.010
There it's important,

00:16:55.010 --> 00:16:57.010
right from beginner level:

00:16:57.010 --> 00:16:59.010
terrain clearance, terrain clearance

00:16:59.010 --> 00:17:01.010
and again terrain clearance.

00:17:01.010 --> 00:17:03.010
Why?

00:17:03.010 --> 00:17:05.010
Because we're next to the terrain the whole time.

00:17:05.010 --> 00:17:07.010
There may be other pilots in the air

00:17:07.010 --> 00:17:09.010
who also want to fly there

00:17:09.010 --> 00:17:11.010
and create a bit of turbulence

00:17:11.010 --> 00:17:13.010
with their aircraft.

00:17:13.010 --> 00:17:15.010
It can quickly get rough

00:17:15.010 --> 00:17:17.010
or there can be a bit more wind

00:17:17.010 --> 00:17:19.010
and it drifts us a bit more

00:17:19.010 --> 00:17:21.010
toward the slope, so we have time

00:17:21.010 --> 00:17:23.010
to react, so we fly away from the slope again.

00:17:23.010 --> 00:17:25.010
And in general,

00:17:25.010 --> 00:17:27.010
always turn the curve away from the slope.

00:17:27.010 --> 00:17:29.010
Never toward the slope.

00:17:29.010 --> 00:17:31.010
Here we have

00:17:31.010 --> 00:17:33.010
tailwind components.

00:17:33.010 --> 00:17:35.010
We have sink-rate components

00:17:35.010 --> 00:17:37.010
from the turn itself.

00:17:37.010 --> 00:17:39.010
It's not predictable.

00:17:39.010 --> 00:17:41.010
And when you fly with a tailwind like that,

00:17:41.010 --> 00:17:43.010
you also have to

00:17:43.010 --> 00:17:45.010
always firmly observe the things listed here

00:17:45.010 --> 00:17:47.390
when soaring.

00:17:47.390 --> 00:17:49.390
Now, depending on the area,

00:17:49.390 --> 00:17:51.440
we naturally also have thermal flying.

00:17:51.440 --> 00:17:53.440
And thermal flying is what's

00:17:53.440 --> 00:17:55.440
probably the supreme discipline

00:17:55.440 --> 00:17:57.680
in paragliding.

00:17:57.680 --> 00:17:59.680
We want to fly as far as possible.

00:17:59.680 --> 00:18:01.680
That means we want to use thermals

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:03.680
as a transporter.

00:18:03.680 --> 00:18:05.680
Because if we only fly in calm air,

00:18:05.680 --> 00:18:07.680
then we have, given our glide ratio,

00:18:07.680 --> 00:18:09.680
if we, for example, launch from 1000 metres,

00:18:09.680 --> 00:18:11.760
then we'd reach 8 kilometres.

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:13.760
In calm air.

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:15.760
But now we have thermals.

00:18:15.760 --> 00:18:17.760
That means I also have to

00:18:17.760 --> 00:18:19.760
know how I

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:21.760
behave with thermals at all

00:18:21.760 --> 00:18:23.900
and how I fly them.

00:18:23.900 --> 00:18:25.900
Thermal flying. So that I can fly thermals,

00:18:25.900 --> 00:18:27.900
I also need to know a few basic rules.

00:18:27.900 --> 00:18:29.900
The easiest, of course,

00:18:29.900 --> 00:18:31.950
is when we have visual confirmation

00:18:31.950 --> 00:18:33.950
via a cloud — then we see

00:18:33.950 --> 00:18:35.950
the thermal optically.

00:18:35.950 --> 00:18:37.950
It's significantly easier to fly that way.

00:18:37.950 --> 00:18:39.950
We'll now take the example of the cloud.

00:18:39.950 --> 00:18:41.950
When we have wind, it's relatively easy

00:18:41.950 --> 00:18:43.950
to find the column.

00:18:43.950 --> 00:18:45.950
Then we simply fly straight under the cloud

00:18:45.950 --> 00:18:47.950
and have found the column relatively quickly.

00:18:47.950 --> 00:18:49.950
Hopefully we can climb.

00:18:49.950 --> 00:18:51.950
The whole thing gets a bit harder when we have wind.

00:18:51.950 --> 00:18:53.950
We'll take the example here

00:18:53.950 --> 00:18:55.950
that the wind comes from the left.

00:18:55.950 --> 00:18:57.950
So the cloud is drifted like that.

00:18:57.950 --> 00:18:59.950
That means, with the wing I now have

00:18:59.950 --> 00:19:01.950
to fly into the upwind side of the cloud,

00:19:01.950 --> 00:19:03.950
so that I can climb nicely in the column

00:19:03.950 --> 00:19:05.950
together with the wind drift

00:19:05.950 --> 00:19:07.950
and optimally catch the thermal.

00:19:07.950 --> 00:19:10.290
The whole thing,

00:19:10.290 --> 00:19:12.290
is relatively simple out in the flatlands,

00:19:12.290 --> 00:19:14.290
also good for practising.

00:19:14.290 --> 00:19:16.290
It gets harder when we

00:19:16.290 --> 00:19:18.290
head into the mountains,

00:19:18.290 --> 00:19:20.290
toward a mountain with a steep face.

00:19:20.290 --> 00:19:22.290
There the thermal is very crisp,

00:19:22.290 --> 00:19:24.430
releases very quickly.

00:19:24.430 --> 00:19:26.430
That means it's not broad,

00:19:26.430 --> 00:19:28.430
but small in area, and accordingly

00:19:28.430 --> 00:19:30.430
rather turbulent.

00:19:30.430 --> 00:19:32.430
That's good if you want to circle very tightly

00:19:32.430 --> 00:19:34.430
very quickly and climb,

00:19:34.430 --> 00:19:36.430
but for a beginner it can very quickly

00:19:36.430 --> 00:19:38.770
lead to being overwhelmed.

00:19:38.770 --> 00:19:40.770
So that you sit nice and loose,

00:19:40.770 --> 00:19:42.770
that you work a lot with weight shift.

00:19:42.770 --> 00:19:44.780
You core the thermal

00:19:44.780 --> 00:19:46.780
nicely on one hand,

00:19:46.780 --> 00:19:48.780
but also work really hard with weight.

00:19:48.780 --> 00:19:50.780
Many pilots do that far too little,

00:19:50.780 --> 00:19:52.780
then work a lot on the brake

00:19:52.780 --> 00:19:54.780
and too little with weight shift.

00:19:54.780 --> 00:19:58.080
A really important point.

00:19:58.080 --> 00:20:00.130
It's also important to leave the thermal,

00:20:00.130 --> 00:20:02.130
the updraft,

00:20:02.130 --> 00:20:04.130
only when you're sure you'll reach the next point,

00:20:04.130 --> 00:20:06.140
the one you'd chosen beforehand.

00:20:06.140 --> 00:20:08.140
as well.

00:20:08.140 --> 00:20:10.140
And that you don't leave too early

00:20:10.140 --> 00:20:12.140
and then don't reach the next mountain at all,

00:20:12.140 --> 00:20:14.140
out in the flatland where you expect the next thermal.

00:20:14.140 --> 00:20:16.140
Instead, it's really important

00:20:16.140 --> 00:20:18.140
that you core the thermal out.

00:20:18.140 --> 00:20:20.140
And it takes a lot of patience,

00:20:20.140 --> 00:20:22.140
to get the altitude you need,

00:20:22.140 --> 00:20:24.140
so that you safely arrive at the next planned point,

00:20:24.140 --> 00:20:26.140
where you assume

00:20:26.140 --> 00:20:28.140
that the next thermal will happen again,

00:20:28.140 --> 00:20:30.140
to take you up again.

00:20:30.140 --> 00:20:32.140
The whole thing naturally takes a lot of experience

00:20:32.140 --> 00:20:34.140
and at the start, be happy

00:20:34.140 --> 00:20:36.140
when you can circle a thermal in the flatland once,

00:20:36.140 --> 00:20:38.140
have a nice, comfortable climb,

00:20:38.140 --> 00:20:40.140
you can enjoy that.

00:20:40.140 --> 00:20:45.100
The success comes with experience.

00:20:45.100 --> 00:20:47.100
In thermal flying we also

00:20:47.100 --> 00:20:49.330
come at some point to situations

00:20:49.330 --> 00:20:51.410
that we might not necessarily want,

00:20:51.410 --> 00:20:53.410
namely that our wing then flies

00:20:53.410 --> 00:20:55.410
in a way we're not used to.

00:20:55.410 --> 00:20:57.410
Asymmetric collapses belong to that,

00:20:57.410 --> 00:20:59.410
frontal collapses might belong to that.

00:20:59.410 --> 00:21:01.410
What we'll cover in this topic

00:21:01.410 --> 00:21:03.410
now,

00:21:03.410 --> 00:21:05.780
sorry,

00:21:05.780 --> 00:21:07.780
what we'll cover, are the flight manoeuvres.

00:21:07.780 --> 00:21:09.780
If you go to the Swiss Hang Gliding Association's

00:21:09.780 --> 00:21:11.780
homepage,

00:21:11.780 --> 00:21:13.780
you also have the exam manoeuvres,

00:21:13.780 --> 00:21:15.780
relevant manoeuvres,

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:17.780
wonderfully explained as video,

00:21:17.780 --> 00:21:19.780
because at the exam too

00:21:19.780 --> 00:21:21.780
you have to be able to fly certain manoeuvres

00:21:21.780 --> 00:21:24.020
of these.

00:21:24.020 --> 00:21:26.020
We start with little-ears,

00:21:26.020 --> 00:21:28.020
which we already heard about earlier in the landing.

00:21:28.020 --> 00:21:30.020
Little-ears is nothing other than

00:21:30.020 --> 00:21:32.020
the outermost A-lines of every wing,

00:21:32.020 --> 00:21:34.020
it's the outermost A-line,

00:21:34.020 --> 00:21:36.130
not to be confused with the stabilo line.

00:21:36.130 --> 00:21:38.130
The stabilo line is the one

00:21:38.130 --> 00:21:40.130
that attaches to the outermost tip of the paraglider,

00:21:40.130 --> 00:21:42.130
is separated and very thin.

00:21:42.130 --> 00:21:44.130
But we have the outermost A-line,

00:21:44.130 --> 00:21:46.130
which we also use to pull the wing up,

00:21:46.130 --> 00:21:48.130
on some paraglider models that's

00:21:48.130 --> 00:21:50.130
separated, sometimes together,

00:21:50.130 --> 00:21:52.130
it's just always the outermost.

00:21:52.130 --> 00:21:54.130
We reach up left and right,

00:21:54.130 --> 00:21:56.130
and then fold in our little-ears.

00:21:56.130 --> 00:21:58.130
We hold them down and can still steer the wing

00:21:58.130 --> 00:22:00.130
with weight shift

00:22:00.130 --> 00:22:02.130
just fine.

00:22:02.130 --> 00:22:04.130
Little-ears are, as I said,

00:22:04.130 --> 00:22:06.130
e.g. when we have a high landing

00:22:06.130 --> 00:22:08.130
and need to come down a bit faster,

00:22:08.130 --> 00:22:10.130
a great manoeuvre.

00:22:10.130 --> 00:22:12.130
Then we can also generate a bit more sink,

00:22:12.130 --> 00:22:14.130
to get to know the wing,

00:22:14.130 --> 00:22:16.130
by pulling little-ears.

00:22:16.130 --> 00:22:18.130
It's an absolutely good manoeuvre.

00:22:18.130 --> 00:22:20.130
There are also big-ears,

00:22:20.130 --> 00:22:22.130
where, depending on the wing model,

00:22:22.130 --> 00:22:24.130
you don't only take the outermost A-line,

00:22:24.130 --> 00:22:26.130
but also the second-outermost,

00:22:26.130 --> 00:22:28.130
if we have three.

00:22:28.130 --> 00:22:30.300
Then much more ear comes in.

00:22:30.300 --> 00:22:32.300
Very important there:

00:22:32.300 --> 00:22:34.300
there are also wings that only have two A-attachments,

00:22:34.300 --> 00:22:36.300
there we mustn't take both in,

00:22:36.300 --> 00:22:38.300
otherwise we'll immediately get a frontal collapse.

00:22:38.300 --> 00:22:40.300
Then all we do

00:22:40.300 --> 00:22:42.700
is grab the ears

00:22:42.700 --> 00:22:44.700
and for big-ears

00:22:44.700 --> 00:22:46.700
we simply take our hand from the inside

00:22:46.700 --> 00:22:48.700
and then bend down.

00:22:48.700 --> 00:22:50.700
This way we pull down about 15-20 cm more line

00:22:50.700 --> 00:22:52.700
and pull them in for big-ears.

00:22:52.700 --> 00:22:54.700
Very important with big-ears,

00:22:54.700 --> 00:22:56.700
simultaneously with this process

00:22:56.700 --> 00:22:58.700
of pulling in the line:

00:22:58.700 --> 00:23:00.700
accelerate.

00:23:00.700 --> 00:23:02.700
Only that way can we prevent

00:23:02.700 --> 00:23:04.700
ending up with too much ear,

00:23:04.700 --> 00:23:06.700
too much drag and the wing flying too slowly,

00:23:06.700 --> 00:23:08.700
and then heading toward parachutal stall.

00:23:08.700 --> 00:23:10.700
By accelerating, by pushing,

00:23:10.700 --> 00:23:12.700
we pull the leading edge here in front back down

00:23:12.700 --> 00:23:14.700
and the wing flies again

00:23:14.700 --> 00:23:16.700
at the normal angle,

00:23:16.700 --> 00:23:18.700
despite the big drag

00:23:18.700 --> 00:23:21.100
that the ears create.

00:23:21.100 --> 00:23:23.100
Then, to open the ears,

00:23:23.100 --> 00:23:25.100
simply let go, and only when the ears

00:23:25.100 --> 00:23:27.100
are fully open,

00:23:27.100 --> 00:23:29.600
then come off the accelerator.

00:23:29.600 --> 00:23:31.600
If we still had the ears in,

00:23:31.600 --> 00:23:33.600
let them go and immediately come off the accelerator,

00:23:33.600 --> 00:23:35.600
then we still have a lot of drag

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:37.600
and the wing flies slowly,

00:23:37.600 --> 00:23:39.600
and when we come off the accelerator,

00:23:39.600 --> 00:23:41.600
we might

00:23:41.600 --> 00:23:43.600
immediately drift toward parachutal stall tendency,

00:23:43.600 --> 00:23:45.870
and we want to prevent that.

00:23:45.870 --> 00:23:47.870
Parachutal stall is nothing other than

00:23:47.870 --> 00:23:49.870
us flying too slowly.

00:23:49.870 --> 00:23:51.870
Our wing should fly, should have forward speed,

00:23:51.870 --> 00:23:53.870
now we've fallen below that.

00:23:53.870 --> 00:23:56.180
Then, before it essentially

00:23:56.180 --> 00:23:58.180
tips backward and fully

00:23:58.180 --> 00:24:00.180
empties the air from the wing,

00:24:00.180 --> 00:24:02.180
there's a pre-stage of parachutal stall.

00:24:02.180 --> 00:24:04.180
The wing is still filled,

00:24:04.180 --> 00:24:06.220
but we no longer have forward speed

00:24:06.220 --> 00:24:08.220
and we only have sink

00:24:08.220 --> 00:24:10.220
and it feels strange.

00:24:10.220 --> 00:24:12.220
The wing is mushy up there.

00:24:12.220 --> 00:24:14.220
Then we've flown too slowly,

00:24:14.220 --> 00:24:16.220
have the brake too far down.

00:24:16.220 --> 00:24:18.220
Or flown with a very wet wing.

00:24:18.220 --> 00:24:20.220
It can also be that one

00:24:20.220 --> 00:24:22.220
ends up in a parachutal stall.

00:24:22.220 --> 00:24:24.220
Then it's basically important,

00:24:24.220 --> 00:24:26.220
we've flown too slowly.

00:24:26.220 --> 00:24:28.220
What's the opposite of slow?

00:24:28.220 --> 00:24:30.220
Fast, so we need to get fast.

00:24:30.220 --> 00:24:32.220
That means: immediately hands on the A-risers

00:24:32.220 --> 00:24:34.220
and push, so you get speed.

00:24:34.220 --> 00:24:36.220
Or also accelerate,

00:24:36.220 --> 00:24:38.220
as the word shows.

00:24:38.220 --> 00:24:40.220
When we hit the accelerator,

00:24:40.220 --> 00:24:42.220
we get the wing back into the normal position.

00:24:42.220 --> 00:24:44.220
So that it picks up speed again

00:24:44.220 --> 00:24:47.490
and we get out of parachutal stall.

00:24:47.490 --> 00:24:49.490
What also goes hand in hand with thermal flying

00:24:49.490 --> 00:24:51.490
is that we're flying

00:24:51.490 --> 00:24:53.490
and we hit a wind shear

00:24:53.490 --> 00:24:55.490
and BANG, the wing is 50% in.

00:24:55.490 --> 00:24:58.020
Completely out of nowhere.

00:24:58.020 --> 00:25:00.020
We get startled first,

00:25:00.020 --> 00:25:02.020
which is normal at the beginning,

00:25:02.020 --> 00:25:04.020
but here too it's important

00:25:04.020 --> 00:25:06.020
that we can react and have to react.

00:25:06.020 --> 00:25:08.020
If we do nothing,

00:25:08.020 --> 00:25:10.020
the wing creates extreme drag after collapsing.

00:25:10.020 --> 00:25:12.020
We still have a slope here,

00:25:12.020 --> 00:25:14.020
and things can go bad relatively quickly.

00:25:14.020 --> 00:25:16.020
That's why it's important

00:25:16.020 --> 00:25:18.020
that we react immediately.

00:25:18.020 --> 00:25:20.020
Whether the collapse is on the inside or outside doesn't matter.

00:25:20.020 --> 00:25:22.020
When the collapse happens,

00:25:22.020 --> 00:25:24.020
our principle must be:

00:25:24.020 --> 00:25:26.020
weight to the opposite side immediately,

00:25:26.020 --> 00:25:28.020
slight brake with the counter-brake,

00:25:28.020 --> 00:25:30.020
if needed,

00:25:30.020 --> 00:25:32.020
so that we can fly straight ahead.

00:25:32.020 --> 00:25:34.020
Here the principle applies again:

00:25:34.020 --> 00:25:36.020
first stabilise, then react.

00:25:36.020 --> 00:25:38.510
Then we can deal with the collapse

00:25:38.510 --> 00:25:40.510
and reopen it.

00:25:40.510 --> 00:25:45.170
If we want to do a rapid descent,

00:25:45.170 --> 00:25:47.170
i.e. come down somewhat faster,

00:25:47.170 --> 00:25:49.170
because, for example,

00:25:49.170 --> 00:25:51.170
we have a thunderstorm approaching

00:25:51.170 --> 00:25:53.170
and we say,

00:25:53.170 --> 00:25:55.170
we don't want to be in the air much longer,

00:25:55.170 --> 00:25:57.170
before the thunderstorm reaches us,

00:25:57.170 --> 00:25:59.180
then it can make sense

00:25:59.180 --> 00:26:01.180
to master certain rapid-descent manoeuvres.

00:26:01.180 --> 00:26:03.180
The big-ears,

00:26:03.180 --> 00:26:05.180
which we discussed earlier,

00:26:05.180 --> 00:26:07.180
is a really important and good descent manoeuvre,

00:26:07.180 --> 00:26:09.180
because with big-ears

00:26:09.180 --> 00:26:11.180
you can still steer with weight

00:26:11.180 --> 00:26:13.180
and if we're in a strong band of lift,

00:26:13.180 --> 00:26:15.180
we fly away from this band of lift

00:26:15.180 --> 00:26:17.180
and don't stay inside it.

00:26:17.180 --> 00:26:19.180
The B-stall, which is also described here

00:26:19.180 --> 00:26:21.180
and asked about at the brevet exam,

00:26:21.180 --> 00:26:23.180
has the big disadvantage

00:26:23.180 --> 00:26:25.180
that we can indeed do it

00:26:25.180 --> 00:26:27.180
and generate quite a lot of sink,

00:26:27.180 --> 00:26:29.180
but we come down on the spot,

00:26:29.180 --> 00:26:31.180
meaning, if we're in the band of lift,

00:26:31.180 --> 00:26:33.180
in the strong one, we're still inside it

00:26:33.180 --> 00:26:35.180
and what we actually want is to fly away.

00:26:35.180 --> 00:26:37.180
B-stall is nothing other than,

00:26:37.180 --> 00:26:39.180
as the name says,

00:26:39.180 --> 00:26:41.180
going to the B-risers,

00:26:41.180 --> 00:26:43.180
pulling the B-risers slowly down to us.

00:26:43.180 --> 00:26:45.180
Important here is

00:26:45.180 --> 00:26:47.180
that we have the brakes normally in our hands,

00:26:47.180 --> 00:26:49.180
not wrapped or anything,

00:26:49.180 --> 00:26:51.180
so that we don't pull them down at the same time,

00:26:51.180 --> 00:26:53.180
but that we pull the B-risers down like this.

00:26:53.180 --> 00:26:55.180
And then a fold appears in the lower surface here

00:26:55.180 --> 00:26:57.180
and I notice

00:26:57.180 --> 00:26:59.180
they only have sink

00:26:59.180 --> 00:27:01.180
and you can hold it for a few seconds

00:27:01.180 --> 00:27:03.420
during a training

00:27:03.420 --> 00:27:05.420
or also under supervision

00:27:05.420 --> 00:27:07.420
of the instructor on the radio,

00:27:07.420 --> 00:27:09.420
you can practise that well.

00:27:09.420 --> 00:27:11.420
Releasing the B-stall is nothing other than

00:27:11.420 --> 00:27:13.470
guiding the initial part slowly

00:27:13.470 --> 00:27:15.470
and then all the way up,

00:27:15.470 --> 00:27:17.470
and here, again, for certain

00:27:17.470 --> 00:27:19.470
flying patterns,

00:27:19.470 --> 00:27:21.470
it's not really a parachutal stall tendency,

00:27:21.470 --> 00:27:23.470
if anything, push the B-risers forward,

00:27:23.470 --> 00:27:26.220
so it flies faster again.

00:27:26.220 --> 00:27:28.220
A spiral dive is a topic of its own.

00:27:28.220 --> 00:27:30.220
It's something

00:27:30.220 --> 00:27:32.220
you should mainly learn under supervision

00:27:32.220 --> 00:27:34.220
or at a SIV course.

00:27:34.220 --> 00:27:36.220
But I'll touch on it very quickly.

00:27:36.220 --> 00:27:38.220
Spiral dive is nothing other than

00:27:38.220 --> 00:27:40.220
a brake,

00:27:40.220 --> 00:27:42.220
a relatively firmly pulled weight

00:27:42.220 --> 00:27:44.220
fully to the side,

00:27:44.220 --> 00:27:46.220
the wing goes into a turn,

00:27:46.220 --> 00:27:48.220
gets faster and faster and faster

00:27:48.220 --> 00:27:50.240
and starts almost screwing itself out of the sky.

00:27:50.240 --> 00:27:52.240
The whole thing happens fairly quickly

00:27:52.240 --> 00:27:54.240
and also takes training

00:27:54.240 --> 00:27:56.240
to exit cleanly.

00:27:56.240 --> 00:27:58.240
That's why you should only learn it under guidance

00:27:58.240 --> 00:28:00.240
and be aware

00:28:00.240 --> 00:28:02.240
that G-forces,

00:28:02.240 --> 00:28:04.240
i.e. the forces acting on you,

00:28:04.240 --> 00:28:06.240
increase very quickly,

00:28:06.240 --> 00:28:08.240
more than you're used to.

00:28:08.240 --> 00:28:10.240
Suppose our weight is 100 kilos.

00:28:10.240 --> 00:28:12.240
Now we go into a strong spiral dive.

00:28:12.240 --> 00:28:14.240
Could it go up to 4G?

00:28:14.240 --> 00:28:16.240
Then 400 kilos are acting on our body.

00:28:16.240 --> 00:28:18.240
And not everyone can tolerate that.

00:28:18.240 --> 00:28:20.240
That's why it's important

00:28:20.240 --> 00:28:22.240
to do proper training

00:28:22.240 --> 00:28:24.240
at a safety course under supervision.

00:28:24.240 --> 00:28:26.240
Or there's also the option

00:28:26.240 --> 00:28:28.240
of the G-Force Trainer,

00:28:28.240 --> 00:28:30.240
where you can wonderfully practise on a simulator

00:28:30.240 --> 00:28:32.240
and get to know

00:28:32.240 --> 00:28:34.240
how you react during spiral-dive stuff.

00:28:34.240 --> 00:28:37.760
A new manoeuvre,

00:28:37.760 --> 00:28:39.760
which isn't going to come up in the theory question,

00:28:39.760 --> 00:28:41.760
but to mention it quickly,

00:28:41.760 --> 00:28:43.760
is doing a spiral dive

00:28:43.760 --> 00:28:45.760
with a collapse held in.

00:28:45.760 --> 00:28:47.760
First you make an asymmetric collapse,

00:28:47.760 --> 00:28:49.760
which we've already discussed,

00:28:49.760 --> 00:28:51.760
and then on the opposite side,

00:28:51.760 --> 00:28:53.760
the one that's open, you do a spiral.

00:28:53.760 --> 00:28:55.760
That has the advantage

00:28:55.760 --> 00:28:57.760
that you generate a lot of sink,

00:28:57.760 --> 00:28:59.760
but have low G-forces.

00:28:59.760 --> 00:29:01.760
It's always those G-forces

00:29:01.760 --> 00:29:03.760
that can pose a danger.

00:29:03.760 --> 00:29:05.760
That's also a manoeuvre,

00:29:05.760 --> 00:29:07.760
that belongs to a sequel,

00:29:07.760 --> 00:29:09.760
with a twist, wing-over and pitching.

00:29:09.760 --> 00:29:11.760
You have to know what those are.

00:29:11.760 --> 00:29:13.760
A spin is nothing other than

00:29:13.760 --> 00:29:15.760
us pulling one side down too much,

00:29:15.760 --> 00:29:17.760
e.g. we wanted to enter a spiral

00:29:17.760 --> 00:29:19.760
to land,

00:29:19.760 --> 00:29:21.760
but did it completely with gross-motor input

00:29:21.760 --> 00:29:23.760
and then one side goes away

00:29:23.760 --> 00:29:25.760
and the wing turns negatively.

00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:29.540
That's a spin.

00:29:29.540 --> 00:29:31.540
If we do that very quickly,

00:29:31.540 --> 00:29:33.540
it can be that the wing turns up there

00:29:33.540 --> 00:29:35.540
and we down here have a momentum,

00:29:35.540 --> 00:29:37.540
where we follow the wing

00:29:37.540 --> 00:29:39.540
too slowly.

00:29:39.540 --> 00:29:41.540
We're still

00:29:41.540 --> 00:29:43.540
in this position from the start.

00:29:43.540 --> 00:29:45.540
Then you can imagine,

00:29:45.540 --> 00:29:47.580
here are our risers,

00:29:47.580 --> 00:29:49.580
very quickly the wing pulls back a bit

00:29:49.580 --> 00:29:51.580
and now I have a twist.

00:29:51.580 --> 00:29:53.580
That means nothing other than

00:29:53.580 --> 00:29:55.920
the risers are crossed.

00:29:55.920 --> 00:29:58.290
Then I'm in a twist.

00:29:58.290 --> 00:30:01.870
That's the term for it.

00:30:01.870 --> 00:30:03.980
If I want to fly a wing-over,

00:30:03.980 --> 00:30:05.980
it's nothing other than

00:30:05.980 --> 00:30:08.420
bringing the wing into a roll.

00:30:08.420 --> 00:30:10.420
That means, I decide

00:30:10.420 --> 00:30:12.420
on one side, left or right,

00:30:12.420 --> 00:30:14.420
and as soon as I come back down inside,

00:30:14.420 --> 00:30:16.420
I'm already giving the opposite side

00:30:16.420 --> 00:30:18.420
the brake input and the weight.

00:30:18.420 --> 00:30:20.420
Whoosh!

00:30:20.420 --> 00:30:22.420
Always weight before brake input.

00:30:22.420 --> 00:30:24.560
And then there are so-called wing-overs.

00:30:24.560 --> 00:30:26.560
That's a fun manoeuvre

00:30:26.560 --> 00:30:28.560
that we also have to

00:30:28.560 --> 00:30:30.560
show on the practical exam.

00:30:30.560 --> 00:30:32.560
It can happen that it comes up.

00:30:32.560 --> 00:30:34.560
There they'll see

00:30:34.560 --> 00:30:36.560
that you get the wing-overs to stabilo height

00:30:36.560 --> 00:30:38.560
each time.

00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:40.560
That means rolling.

00:30:40.560 --> 00:30:42.670
That's nothing other than wing-overs.

00:30:42.670 --> 00:30:44.670
And it's fun.

00:30:44.670 --> 00:30:46.670
It's a good manoeuvre

00:30:46.670 --> 00:30:48.670
to get to know the wing and train.

00:30:48.670 --> 00:30:50.670
Same with pitching.

00:30:50.670 --> 00:30:52.670
Pitching is nothing other than

00:30:52.670 --> 00:30:54.670
braking the wing hard.

00:30:54.670 --> 00:30:56.670
The wing goes back.

00:30:56.670 --> 00:30:59.140
We as the person go forward.

00:30:59.140 --> 00:31:01.140
And now we wait

00:31:01.140 --> 00:31:03.140
until the wing comes forward again

00:31:03.140 --> 00:31:05.140
and shoots forward.

00:31:05.140 --> 00:31:07.140
Wait until we swing through underneath.

00:31:07.140 --> 00:31:09.140
Now we want to brake again.

00:31:09.140 --> 00:31:11.140
We really have to wait

00:31:11.140 --> 00:31:13.140
until we're past the lowest point

00:31:13.140 --> 00:31:15.140
and then brake again,

00:31:15.140 --> 00:31:17.140
so we get a pitching motion.

00:31:17.140 --> 00:31:19.140
There too they'll see on the exam

00:31:19.140 --> 00:31:21.500
that you pitch to the trailing edge

00:31:21.500 --> 00:31:23.500
and leading edge.

00:31:23.500 --> 00:31:25.500
It's not an insanely strong pitch,

00:31:25.500 --> 00:31:27.500
but we have to manage it on the wing.

00:31:27.500 --> 00:31:29.500
That's the goal,

00:31:29.500 --> 00:31:32.100
that we get to know the whole thing.

00:31:32.100 --> 00:31:34.100
Now the spin-twist manoeuvre

00:31:34.100 --> 00:31:36.100
like wing-over and pitching.

00:31:36.100 --> 00:31:38.100
All that can be a lot of fun

00:31:38.100 --> 00:31:40.100
and makes absolute sense.

00:31:40.100 --> 00:31:42.100
For training.

00:31:42.100 --> 00:31:44.100
Now it can also be

00:31:44.100 --> 00:31:47.600
that the whole thing goes pear-shaped.

00:31:47.600 --> 00:31:49.680
And then the topic

00:31:49.680 --> 00:31:51.680
of the reserve parachute

00:31:51.680 --> 00:31:53.680
comes into play in the next chapter.

00:31:53.680 --> 00:31:56.660
You have to be aware,

00:31:56.660 --> 00:31:58.660
your reserve parachute

00:31:58.660 --> 00:32:02.020
is no use.

00:32:02.020 --> 00:32:04.020
It's absolutely useless,

00:32:04.020 --> 00:32:06.020
your reserve parachute.

00:32:06.020 --> 00:32:08.190
If you don't pull it.

00:32:08.190 --> 00:32:10.190
That's a really important principle.

00:32:10.190 --> 00:32:12.190
Skydivers have a system

00:32:12.190 --> 00:32:14.190
where if they've passed a certain altitude,

00:32:14.190 --> 00:32:16.190
the system automatically

00:32:16.190 --> 00:32:18.190
deploys the reserve.

00:32:18.190 --> 00:32:20.190
We paragliders don't have that.

00:32:20.190 --> 00:32:22.190
And due to the design, nobody has yet

00:32:22.190 --> 00:32:24.190
managed to find a solution for it.

00:32:24.190 --> 00:32:26.190
That means, in an emergency situation

00:32:26.190 --> 00:32:28.190
we as pilots actively have to

00:32:28.190 --> 00:32:30.190
pull the reserve.

00:32:30.190 --> 00:32:32.210
And only when we pull it

00:32:32.210 --> 00:32:34.640
does it actually work.

00:32:34.640 --> 00:32:37.330
We have to be very firmly aware of that.

00:32:37.330 --> 00:32:39.330
If we have a situation,

00:32:39.330 --> 00:32:41.570
out of control,

00:32:41.570 --> 00:32:43.570
this situation isn't going to improve.

00:32:43.570 --> 00:32:45.940
It only improves

00:32:45.940 --> 00:32:47.940
when we say,

00:32:47.940 --> 00:32:49.940
now it's no longer good,

00:32:49.940 --> 00:32:53.010
now I'm out of control,

00:32:53.010 --> 00:32:55.010
now I have to pull my reserve.

00:32:55.010 --> 00:32:57.010
When I pull it,

00:32:57.010 --> 00:32:59.010
the principle is always:

00:32:59.010 --> 00:33:01.010
when it's uncontrollable.

00:33:01.010 --> 00:33:03.010
Meaning, I have a state

00:33:03.010 --> 00:33:05.010
where I no longer know

00:33:05.010 --> 00:33:07.010
where up and down are.

00:33:07.010 --> 00:33:09.010
And this state doesn't stabilise

00:33:09.010 --> 00:33:11.010
within the shortened time,

00:33:11.010 --> 00:33:13.010
we're talking 2-3 seconds,

00:33:13.010 --> 00:33:15.010
that's time for the reserve.

00:33:15.010 --> 00:33:17.010
If I have little altitude in the whole thing,

00:33:17.010 --> 00:33:19.010
meaning, I was at the altitude-loss area in the landing zone

00:33:19.010 --> 00:33:21.010
and I have low altitude anyway

00:33:21.010 --> 00:33:23.010
and I have a problem,

00:33:23.010 --> 00:33:25.010
pull the reserve immediately.

00:33:25.010 --> 00:33:27.010
Out of control,

00:33:27.010 --> 00:33:29.020
I no longer know what the wing is doing,

00:33:29.020 --> 00:33:31.100
pull the reserve immediately.

00:33:31.100 --> 00:33:33.100
It can happen from a collapse,

00:33:33.100 --> 00:33:35.100
it can happen that you've braked too hard,

00:33:35.100 --> 00:33:37.100
as we saw earlier,

00:33:37.100 --> 00:33:39.100
a spin happens, something uncontrolled,

00:33:39.100 --> 00:33:41.100
straight to the reserve.

00:33:41.100 --> 00:33:43.100
It can also be that

00:33:43.100 --> 00:33:45.100
we have quite a lot of space in the air,

00:33:45.100 --> 00:33:47.100
but other airspace users

00:33:47.100 --> 00:33:49.100
and if we have a collision,

00:33:49.100 --> 00:33:51.100
then it's definitely also time

00:33:51.100 --> 00:33:53.100
to pull the reserve.

00:33:53.100 --> 00:33:55.220
Because we know ourselves,

00:33:55.220 --> 00:33:57.220
if we've had the collision

00:33:57.220 --> 00:33:59.220
and are flying again,

00:33:59.220 --> 00:34:01.220
we don't know,

00:34:01.220 --> 00:34:03.220
is our aircraft so badly damaged

00:34:03.220 --> 00:34:05.220
that maybe only then will we notice,

00:34:05.220 --> 00:34:07.220
when we're on landing approach,

00:34:07.220 --> 00:34:09.460
meaning we can no longer react

00:34:09.460 --> 00:34:11.460
and pull the reserve.

00:34:11.460 --> 00:34:13.460
It can also happen

00:34:13.460 --> 00:34:15.460
that you fly over a big field,

00:34:15.460 --> 00:34:17.460
pull the reserve,

00:34:17.460 --> 00:34:19.460
if you're already out of control anyway,

00:34:19.460 --> 00:34:21.460
the first principle comes back,

00:34:21.460 --> 00:34:23.460
the principle to keep in mind,

00:34:23.460 --> 00:34:25.460
and pull the reserve immediately.

00:34:25.460 --> 00:34:27.470
It can also be

00:34:27.470 --> 00:34:29.470
that you have a medical problem,

00:34:29.470 --> 00:34:31.470
you launch and things go black before your eyes,

00:34:31.470 --> 00:34:33.470
something wasn't okay,

00:34:33.470 --> 00:34:35.470
then the reserve is the best option,

00:34:35.470 --> 00:34:37.650
flying somewhere unconscious into the terrain

00:34:37.650 --> 00:34:40.020
with the paraglider is no good option.

00:34:40.020 --> 00:34:42.020
What happens very rarely these days,

00:34:42.020 --> 00:34:44.020
or essentially no longer happens,

00:34:44.020 --> 00:34:46.020
is material failure,

00:34:46.020 --> 00:34:48.020
but it could still happen

00:34:48.020 --> 00:34:50.020
that it does after all.

00:34:50.020 --> 00:34:52.020
You notice something on the harness

00:34:52.020 --> 00:34:54.020
is no longer as it should be

00:34:54.020 --> 00:34:56.020
and you have a flight path because of that

00:34:56.020 --> 00:34:58.020
that you can hardly hold,

00:34:58.020 --> 00:35:00.020
because you're sitting crooked in the harness,

00:35:00.020 --> 00:35:05.710
because something has torn,

00:35:05.710 --> 00:35:09.140
then it's definitely also a case for the reserve.

00:35:09.140 --> 00:35:11.140
The principle of the second chance,

00:35:11.140 --> 00:35:13.150
whenever it's uncontrolled,

00:35:13.150 --> 00:35:15.150
that the reserve is useful,

00:35:15.150 --> 00:35:17.150
is really, really important for all of flying.

00:35:17.150 --> 00:35:19.150
I say second chance deliberately,

00:35:19.150 --> 00:35:21.150
when we have it

00:35:21.150 --> 00:35:23.260
and have to know

00:35:23.260 --> 00:35:25.260
how the whole system works.

00:35:25.260 --> 00:35:27.260
How that works,

00:35:27.260 --> 00:35:29.260
you absolutely have to ask

00:35:29.260 --> 00:35:31.260
at your flight school.

00:35:31.260 --> 00:35:33.260
You have to train it in the harness,

00:35:33.260 --> 00:35:35.260
so you know where the reserve handle is.

00:35:35.260 --> 00:35:37.260
A good exercise for that is also,

00:35:37.260 --> 00:35:39.260
if you fly out on a normal flight,

00:35:39.260 --> 00:35:41.260
with a flat hand,

00:35:41.260 --> 00:35:43.260
on every flight,

00:35:43.260 --> 00:35:45.260
where the reserve is,

00:35:45.260 --> 00:35:47.260
so that in an emergency you'll also know

00:35:47.260 --> 00:35:49.600
how to react.

00:35:49.600 --> 00:35:51.600
The reserve is a large topic,

00:35:51.600 --> 00:35:53.600
there are more things that belong to it,

00:35:53.600 --> 00:35:55.600
like how much you have to pack.

00:35:55.600 --> 00:35:57.600
Like, for example, manufacturers saying:

00:35:57.600 --> 00:35:59.600
repack fresh every six months.

00:35:59.600 --> 00:36:01.600
Practice shows a bit

00:36:01.600 --> 00:36:03.600
of six months to one year.

00:36:03.600 --> 00:36:05.600
Anything else, you really shouldn't do,

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:07.600
packed for longer than a year,

00:36:07.600 --> 00:36:09.600
but it needs to be re-folded.

00:36:09.600 --> 00:36:11.600
That's a big topic

00:36:11.600 --> 00:36:13.600
and a course

00:36:13.600 --> 00:36:15.600
in its own right.

00:36:15.600 --> 00:36:17.600
What we've discussed here,

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:19.600
the flight practice,

00:36:19.600 --> 00:36:22.160
that's what's

00:36:22.160 --> 00:36:24.160
asked about on the exam.

00:36:24.160 --> 00:36:26.160
You have to know it.

00:36:26.160 --> 00:36:28.160
I hope you enjoyed this lecture.

00:36:28.160 --> 00:36:30.210
I want to thank you very much

00:36:30.210 --> 00:36:32.210
for your attention

00:36:32.210 --> 00:36:34.260
and see you soon in the air.
